      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions used for validation must be documented and match the range of COU operating conditions at Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "Bench validation experiments conducted at 3, 4, and 5 L/min flow rates at 3000 and 3500 RPM, spanning the 5 COU operating points. Blood analog fluid (glycerol-water, viscosity matched) used. Temperature, inlet pressure, and rotational speed logged at 100 Hz throughout each run."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted QoI must be compared to experimental measurements with quantified agreement metrics at Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "Normalized hemolysis index predictions compared to experimental NIH values across all 5 operating points. Mean absolute error was 8.4% with no systematic bias. Bland-Altman analysis showed limits of agreement within ±15%, meeting the acceptance threshold."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation QoI must be directly relevant to the COU decision quantity (relative hemolysis index) at Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "The primary validation QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH), which maps directly to the relative hemolysis index (RH) used in the COU acceptance criterion. Shear stress scalar and exposure time are intermediate QoIs that feed the power-law hemolysis model, confirming full QoI relevance chain."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
